{
  "text": "Let us come back to the implicit assumption 1). Hull and Townsend [CITATION_1] have shown that scale-invariant but not conformally-invariant unitary theories exist among 2D sigma-models with non-compact target space. These models likely violate assumption 1), and perhaps also 2) [CITATION_2] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "121406895",
    "[CITATION_2]": "122981363"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "121406895": {
      "title": "Finiteness And Conformal Invariance In Nonlinear Sigma Models",
      "abstract": "Abstract We show that two-dimensional non-linear sigma models that are finite to some order in perturbation theory need not be conformally invariant to that order, although they may be invariant under rigid scale transformations. We give the conditions sufficient for one-loop conformal invariance and discuss implications for string theory."
    },
    "122981363": {
      "title": "Scale And Conformal Invariance In Quantum Field Theory",
      "abstract": "Abstract We study the relation between invariance under rigid and local changes of length scale. In two dimensions, we complete an argument of Zamolodchikov showing that the rigid invariance implies the local under broad conditions. In three or more dimensions we are unable to find either a general proof or a counterexample, but we find some new conformally invariant systems."
    }
  }
}